07175nam a22011295i 9780823280131DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232801317 a10.1515/97808232801312doi  a(DE-B1597)555101  a(OCoLC)1038057674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a364.660122300aDeconstructing the Death Penalty :bDerrida's Seminars and the New Abolitionism /ced. by Kelly Oliver, Stephanie Straub. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tintroduction. From Capital Punishment to Abolitionism: Deconstructing the Death Penalty -- tpart I. Reading Derrida’s Death Penalty Seminars -- tchapter 1. Beginning with Literature -- tchapter 2. A New Primal Scene: Derrida and the Scene of Execution -- tchapter 3. Always the Other Who Decides -- tchapter 4. The Death Penalty and Its Exceptions -- tpart II. Derrida and His Interlocutors -- tchapter 5. Derrida at Montaigne -- tchapter 6. “Bidding Up” on the Question of Sovereignty -- tchapter 7. Calculus -- tpart III. Extending Derrida’s Analysis -- tchapter 8. A Proper Death -- tchapter 9. Figures of Interest -- tchapter 10. Opening the Blinds on Botched Executions -- tpart IV. Derrida and Capital Punishment in the United States -- tchapter 11. Furman and Finitude -- tchapter 12. The Heart of the Other? -- tchapter 13. An Abolitionism Worthy of the Name -- tcontributors -- tindex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume represents the first collection of essays devoted exclusively to Jacques Derrida's Death Penalty Seminars, conducted from 1999 to 2001. The volume includes essays from a range of scholars working in philosophy, law, Francophone studies, and comparative literature, including established Derridians, activist scholars, and emerging scholars. These essays attempt to elucidate and expand upon Derrida's deconstruction of the theologico-political logic of the death penalty in order to construct a new form of abolitionism, one not rooted in the problematic logics of sovereign power. These essays provide remarkable insight into Derrida’s ethical and political projects; this volume will not only explore the implications of Derrida’s thought on capital punishment and mass incarceration, but will also help to further elucidate the philosophical groundwork for his later deconstructions of sovereign power and the human/animal divide. Because Derrida is deconstructing the logic of the death penalty, rather than the death penalty itself, his seminars will prove useful to scholars and activists opposing all forms of state sanctioned killing. In compiling this volume, our goals were twofold: first, to make a case for Derrida's continuing importance in debates on capital punishment, mass incarceration, and police brutality, and second, to construct a new, versatile abolitionism, one capable of confronting all forms the death penalty might take.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCapital punishmentxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aCapital punishmentxPhilosophy. 0aImprisonmentxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPower (Social sciences). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh  aCapital Punishment.  aDeath Penalty Abolition.  aDeath Penalty.  aDeconstruction.  aJacques Derrida.  aMass Incarceration.  aPolitical Theology.  aPrison Industrial Complex.  aPsychoanalysis.  aSovereignty.1 aAnderson, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Nicole.1 aChenoweth, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen